Detecting outliers

What data points are considered outliers depends on your model, so the first step is to set estimate your model with the lm function. You can then compute the four outlier detection measures with the following functions:

  • Mahalanobis distance: mahalanobis(x,center,cov,...) where x is a matrix (or data.frame) with the predictors for which you want to compute the distance, and center a vector with the means of the predictors, and cov a covariance matrix for the predictors. For convenience, you can also use the myMahalanobis function defined below…
  • leverage: hatvalues(model,...) where model is the estimated regression model (estimated with the lm function)
  • Studentized deleted residual: rstudent(model,...)
  • Cook’s distance:cooks.distance(model,...)

There are different guidelines as to whether a particular data point is an outlier according to these four measures:

  • The Mahalanobis distance follows a \(\chi^2\)-distribution with \(p-1\) degrees of freedom (for \(p\) parameters in the model and hence \(p-1\) predictors). Usually, when you have a very small sample (\(n = 30\)) and only two predictors in your model, only values greater than 11 are cause for concern.
  • The average leverage value for each participant in the data is \(\overline{h} = \frac{p}{n}\) where \(p\) is the number of parameters. Individual leverage values that are more than twice or three times the average are cause for concern.
  • The studentized deleted residual follows a \(t\)-distribution with \(n-p-1\) degrees of freedom, so you can look up the critical cut-off value in a table of t-values. Make sure to correct your \(\alpha\) to take into account that you want a two-sided test and that you’re “running” multiple tests (i.e. to correct for the family-wise error)!
  • For Cook’s distance, values greater than 1 or 2 indicate possible problems.

The easiest way to remove the outliers from your data-set is to use the subset function, which was discussed in the lab hand-out for lecture 2.

As an example, I will show you how to use these measures with a dataset we analysed last week:

# load the SAWBS data

mod <- lm(edicomp~rses+bdi+bmi+sawbs+wtpercep+shpercep,data=geller)

Example of Mahalanobis distance

# compute the Mahalanobis distance for the predictors
# first, lets put the predictors in a matrix called x
predictors <- as.matrix(geller[,c("ses","bdi","bmi","sawbs","wtpercep","shpercep")])
mahal <- mahalanobis(predictors,colMeans(predictors),cov(predictors))
# define a convenience function...
myMahalanobis <- function(x) {
  x <- as.matrix(x)
  mahalanobis(x,colMeans(x),cov(x))
}
mahal <- myMahalanobis(predictors)
summary(mahal)
##    Min. 1st Qu.  Median    Mean 3rd Qu.    Max. 
##  0.8789  3.8100  5.7970  5.9290  7.7550 13.8900
## critical value without correction
qchisq(1-.05,df=ncol(predictors))
## [1] 12.59159
# check which observations are above this critical value
which(mahal >= qchisq(1-.05,df=ncol(predictors)))
## [1] 10
# critical value with bonferonni correction
qchisq(1-.05/nrow(geller),df=ncol(predictors))
## [1] 23.69084
# check which observations are above this critical value
which(mahal >= qchisq(1-.05/nrow(predictors),df=ncol(predictors)))
## integer(0)

Example of leverage

lever <- hatvalues(mod)
# mod has 7 parameters, so a large leverage would be 2*7/n
which(lever > (2*7)/nrow(geller))
## 61 
## 61

Example of Studentized deleted residual

sdr <- rstudent(mod)
## critical value without correction
# note that the t-distribution is two-sided, 
# which is why alpha/2 is used below
qt(1-.05/2,df=nrow(geller)-7-1)
## [1] 1.991673
which(abs(sdr) >= qt(1-.05/2,df=nrow(geller)-7-1))
## 33 34 41 59 63 
## 33 34 41 59 63
## critical value with bonferonni correction
qt(1-(.05/2)/nrow(geller),df=nrow(geller)-7-1)
## [1] 3.583904
which(abs(sdr) >= qt(1-(.05/2)/nrow(geller),df=nrow(geller)-7-1))
## named integer(0)

Example of Cooks distance

cooksd <- cooks.distance(mod)
summary(cooksd)
##      Min.   1st Qu.    Median      Mean   3rd Qu.      Max. 
## 5.120e-06 8.623e-04 4.183e-03 1.227e-02 1.473e-02 7.310e-02
which(cooksd >= 2)
## named integer(0)

Selecting cases based on multiple criteria

To select those cases which are not likely to be outliers, you can use something like the following:

clean_dat <- subset(geller,cooksd < 2 & abs(sdr) < qt(1-(.05/2)/nrow(geller),df=nrow(geller)-7-1) & lever < (2*7)/nrow(geller) & mahal < qchisq(1-.05/nrow(predictors),df=7))
summary(clean_dat)

Multicollinearity

To assess whether any of your predictors are collinear (i.e. whether there is multicollinearity in your model), you can compute the Variance Inflation Factor through the vif function in the car package:

# load the car package
library(car)
# compute the VIF for each predictor in the model 
vif(mod)
##     rses      bdi      bmi    sawbs wtpercep shpercep 
## 2.747457 3.101769 1.745329 1.331568 2.468101 1.640906

The tolerance can be derived from the VIF simply as \(frac{1}{\text{VIF}}\), so

# compute the tolerance
1/vif(mod)
##      rses       bdi       bmi     sawbs  wtpercep  shpercep 
## 0.3639730 0.3223967 0.5729578 0.7509942 0.4051699 0.6094196

A common heuristic is that tolerance values below .200 and certainly below .100 are cause for concern.

Predicted-vs.-residuals plot

You can use a predicted-vs.-residuals plot to check whether the assumptions of unbiased and homoscedastic errors are met or violated. From an estimated model, You can create this plot easily yourself as follows:

plot(predict(mod),residuals(mod))

Alternatively, you can ask for a number of diagnostic plots for an estimated model by calling the plot function with the model as first argument:

plot(mod)

Histogram and Q-Q plot

If you want to check the assumption of normality of the errors, you can create a histogram or Q-Q plot for the residuals.

hist(residuals(mod))

If you want a histogram with a Normal distribution overlaid, you can do this as

hist(residuals(mod),prob=TRUE)
curve(dnorm(x,mean=0,sd=sd(residuals(mod))),add=TRUE)

A Q-Q-plot can be created as

qqnorm(residuals(mod))
qqline(residuals(mod), col = 2)

The Q-Q plot was also created in the output of the call to plot above. Finally, you can also use the “fancy” qqplot function I made available on Moodle.

Test for Normality

You can perform the Shapiro-Wilks tests for Normality through the shapiro.test function. The more general, but less powerful, Kolmogorov-Smirnov test can be performed through the ks.test function.

shapiro.test(residuals(mod))
## 
##  Shapiro-Wilk normality test
## 
## data:  residuals(mod)
## W = 0.98351, p-value = 0.3592
ks.test(residuals(mod),"pnorm",mean=0,sd=sd(residuals(mod)))
## 
##  One-sample Kolmogorov-Smirnov test
## 
## data:  residuals(mod)
## D = 0.090797, p-value = 0.4657
## alternative hypothesis: two-sided

The results of the Kolmogorov-Smirnov and Shapiro-Wilk tests should not be significant. If they are, that means your residuals deviate significantly from a normal distribution.
